Yes, you should refresh the cache after delete — same as you do after create/update in `CreateOrUpdateModelExpressionRuleAsync`:

```csharp
public async Task DeleteModelExpressionRulesAsync(string ownerId, IList<Rule> rules, int operationConfirmed, CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    foreach (var rule in rules)
    {
        var deleteCommand = _sprocContext.DeleteSprocCommand<Rule>(ownerId);
        await deleteCommand.WithParameters(new SprocParameter("rule_id", rule.Lid))
            .ExecuteAsync(cancellationToken).ConfigureAwait(false);
    }

    await RefreshModelExpressionRulesCache(ownerId, cancellationToken).ConfigureAwait(false);
}
```

Without this, the cache will still serve the deleted rules until the next cache refresh cycle, causing stale data issues (e.g., deleted rules still appearing in the Templates → Rules grid).
